    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix bounds checking in EMM FSM string conversion functions\n\n### Summary\nThe EMM FSM string conversion functions `emm_fsm_event2str` and `emm_fsm_status2str` in the NAS stack were missing bounds checking. When called with invalid indices, these functions would cause undefined behavior including potential crashes or returning garbage data. This could lead to missed scheduling opportunities where UE scheduling logic might be skipped due to invalid string values.\n\nThis fix adds proper bounds checking to both functions to ensure they always return valid strings.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/EMM/SAP/emm_fsm.c`: Added bounds checking to `emm_fsm_event2str` and `emm_fsm_status2str` functions.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Send a NAS message with an invalid EMM primitive value (0 or >= 27)\n2. Observe that `emm_fsm_event2str` gets called with an out-of-bounds index\n3. The function would previously cause undefined behavior (segfault or garbage return values)\n4. This could lead to incorrect logging and potentially missed UE scheduling opportunities\n\n### Expected Behavior After Fix\n- Invalid indices now return \"UNKNOWN\" string instead of causing undefined behavior\n- UE scheduling logic should no longer be affected by invalid EMM event values\n- System stability is improved when handling malformed or unexpected NAS messages\n"
}